# FinTrack Frontend Rules

Apply these rules to all frontend changes.

## Core Architecture
- Use Vue 3 with `<script setup lang="ts">` only; never use Options API.
- Keep architecture flow: `View -> Service -> Store -> State`.
- Views/components must not contain business logic.
- Components/views must never generate IDs or set `createdAt`/`updatedAt`.
- Keep typed parameters and return types in functions.
- For local variables with obvious inferred types, explicit type annotations are optional.

## Components
- Reusable UI only; not route pages.
- Follow Single Responsibility Principle.
- Use PascalCase filenames (e.g., `UserCard.vue`).
- Type props with `defineProps<T>()`.
- Type emits with `defineEmits<T>()`.
- Avoid raw logic in templates; move transformations to computed or typed methods.

## Views and Router
- Views are SFC `.vue` files named `PascalCaseView.vue`.
- Each route maps to exactly one View.
- Routes must use named routes and dot notation for nested names.
- Keep RESTful paths.
- Use route `meta` fields for title/auth.
- Define authentication guards in router config, never inside views.

## Store, Services, DTOs, Interfaces
- Use Pinia setup stores with typed state and one store per domain.
- Store actions modify state; avoid direct logic-heavy mutation from components.
- Store IDs must be camelCase (`useUserStore`).
- Services must be classes with static methods and one service per domain.
- Services handle business logic and store interaction.
- Create methods accept DTO inputs; services generate IDs/timestamps when needed.
- DTOs represent input data only; avoid `id` and generated fields.
- Keep one interface per file in `interfaces/` named `PascalCaseInterface`.
- Use camelCase properties and `Date` type for dates (after parsing API values).

## Imports, Utils, and Errors
- Import groups:
  1) External packages
  2) Internal aliases (`@/`)
- Keep alphabetical order within each group.
- Use `@/` alias for `src/`.
- Utils must be classes with static methods; no loose functions, no side effects.
- Do not access stores/services from utils.
- Handle errors in the correct layer and expose user-friendly UI messages.
